# Plan: Add "mistral-instruct-v3" Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 uses a simple `[INST]`/`[/INST]` chat format that prepends system messages into the first user turn and appends `</s>` after assistant turns. It does **not** use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` tags (unlike Mistral v7/Ministral 3) and has no tool-calling markers. A specialized handler ensures reliable prompt construction and output parsing for this format without relying on the autoparser.

The constraint is: **only add new code** — do not modify existing handler bodies or the header file (`src/llama-chat.h`). This rules out the legacy enum-based system and points to the specialized handler system in `common/chat.cpp`.

---

## Step 1: Add the handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

**File:** `common/chat.cpp`  
**Location:** Insert the new `static` function immediately before `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (before line 1634).

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
    const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs)
{
    common_chat_params data;
    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;
    return data;
}
```

**Rationale:**
- Calls `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()` to render the Jinja template (same pattern as all other specialized handlers).
- Uses `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` since Mistral Instruct v0.3 has no tool-call markers or structured output in its base format. No PEG parser or grammar is needed.
- Follows the existing handler signature: `static common_chat_params fn(const common_chat_template&, const autoparser::generation_params&)`.

---

## Step 2: Add detection clause in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**File:** `common/chat.cpp`  
**Location:** Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (starts at line 1634). Add a new `if` block **after** the existing Ministral 3 check (line 1644) and **before** the GPT-OSS check (line 1646).

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 — uses [INST]/[/INST] but no [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
// Distinguishes from Ministral/Magistral (which has [SYSTEM_PROMPT]) and from
// Llama 2 variants (which use <<SYS>>).
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Detection logic explained:**
- `[INST]` present → confirms this is an INST-style template.
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent → distinguishes from Ministral 3 (which has `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` + `[TOOL_CALLS]` + `[ARGS]`) and from Mistral v7 (which has `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`).
- Placement **after** the Ministral 3 check is important: the Ministral 3 check already exits early for templates with `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` + `[TOOL_CALLS]` + `[ARGS]`, so by the time we reach our check, those have been handled. Our check then catches simpler `[INST]`-based templates without `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`.

---

## Step 3: Add test case in `tests/test-chat-template.cpp`

**File:** `tests/test-chat-template.cpp`  
**Location:** In the `test_cases` vector, after the existing Mistral v7 test (around line 559), add a new entry.

Use the actual Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 Jinja template (which is the "v1" template format with system-message support). The Jinja template is already present as the v0.2 "v1 template" test at line 529 — we add a separate named entry to explicitly test the specialized handler path.

```cpp
{
    /* .name= */ "mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 (mistral-instruct-v3 specialized handler)",
    /* .template_str= */ "{%- if messages[0]['role'] == 'system' %}\n    {%- set system_message = messages[0]['content'] %}\n    {%- set loop_messages = messages[1:] %}\n{%- else %}\n    {%- set loop_messages = messages %}\n{%- endif %}\n\n{{- bos_token }}\n{%- for message in loop_messages %}\n    {%- if (message['role'] == 'user') != (loop.index0 % 2 == 0) %}\n        {{- raise_exception('After the optional system message, conversation roles must alternate user/assistant/user/assistant/...') }}\n    {%- endif %}\n    {%- if message['role'] == 'user' %}\n        {%- if loop.first and system_message is defined %}\n            {{- ' [INST] ' + system_message + '\\n\\n' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}\n        {%- else %}\n            {{- ' [INST] ' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}\n        {%- endif %}\n    {%- elif message['role'] == 'assistant' %}\n        {{- ' ' + message['content'] + eos_token}}\n    {%- else %}\n        {{- raise_exception('Only user and assistant roles are supported, with the exception of an initial optional system message!') }}\n    {%- endif %}\n{%- endfor %}\n",
    /* .expected_output= */       " [INST] You are a helpful assistant\n\nHello [/INST] Hi there</s> [INST] Who are you [/INST]    I am an assistant   </s> [INST] Another question [/INST]",
    /* .expected_output_jinja= */ " [INST] You are a helpful assistant\n\nHello [/INST] Hi there</s> [INST] Who are you [/INST]    I am an assistant   </s> [INST] Another question [/INST]",
    /* .bos_token= */ "",
    /* .eos_token= */ "</s>",
},
```

---

## Summary of changes

| File | Change | Type |
|------|--------|------|
| `common/chat.cpp` ~line 1633 | Add `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3()` function | New function |
| `common/chat.cpp` ~line 1644 | Add detection `if` block in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` | New code block |
| `tests/test-chat-template.cpp` ~line 559 | Add test case entry for the new handler | New test entry |

No existing handler functions are modified. No header files are changed.

---

## Verification

1. **Build:** `cmake --build build -j` — confirm compilation succeeds with the new code.
2. **Run chat template tests:** `./build/bin/test-chat-template` — confirm all existing tests still pass and the new Mistral v0.3 test passes.
3. **Manual sanity check:** Verify the detection logic by checking that:
   - A template with `[INST]` but no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` routes to the new handler (check for `LOG_DBG` output).
   - A template with `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` + `[TOOL_CALLS]` + `[ARGS]` still routes to the Ministral 3 handler.
   - A template with `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (e.g., Mistral v7) does NOT route to the new handler.

